This Somali spot is in the back corner of a VTA light rail parking lot, and it was relatively quiet when I showed up for a weekday lunch. I actually first heard about it on local PBS TV program Check, Please! Bay Area and my cousin vouched for its enjoyability. Having eaten there before, he steered the ship for our order.\n\nSports Plate ($29.99): their 2-person dish. Went with beef and goat for the proteins and just rice for the starch, although you can get two carbs, the other options being pasta, chappatti, and injera. The proteins were delicious, tender, and not dry. The goat in particular was sufficiently gamey but not overly so. The rice was cooked properly seasoned deliciously. The veggies came in a huge variety, including even something like a water chestnut. The green sauce on the side (which you can request more of) was tasty and just moderately spicy. Considering that this is an San Jose, it&#x27;s a bargain for the portion, which can even feed 3 or 4 for lunch.\n\nSambuso ($2): their version of a samosa. Great crispy and flaky exterior. Veggies instead of potatoes, and ground meat. Reasonable size for an appetizer (although it was actually served after the entree) and for the price. A must-try here.\n\nMandazi ($1.50): a puffy and fluffy bread. Lightly sweet, so it goes well with the complimentary sweet and cinnamon-y tea (pour it yourself in the back) or with the entrees. I&#x27;d recommend ordering at least one to share, if not entirely for yourself. You might even accidentally get one when trying to order multiple Sambusos as I did.\n\nI&#x27;d definitely recommend Jubba for a great lunch or dinner for anyone who enjoys meat and starches. This Somali spot is in the back corner of a VTA light rail parking lot, and it was relatively quiet when I showed up for a weekday lunch. I actually first heard about it on local PBS TV program Check, Please! Bay Area and my cousin vouched for its enjoyability. Having eaten there before, he steered the ship for our order.\n\nSports Plate ($29.99): their 2-person dish. Went with beef and goat for the proteins and just rice for the starch, although you can get two carbs, the other options being pasta, chappatti, and injera. The proteins were delicious, tender, and not dry. The goat in particular was sufficiently gamey but not overly so. The rice was cooked properly seasoned deliciously. The veggies came in a huge variety, including even something like a water chestnut. The green sauce on the side (which you can request more of) was tasty and just moderately spicy. Considering that this is an San Jose, it&#x27;s a bargain for the portion, which can even feed 3 or 4 for lunch.\n\nSambuso ($2): their version of a samosa. Great crispy and flaky exterior. Veggies instead of potatoes, and ground meat. Reasonable size for an appetizer (although it was actually served after the entree) and for the price. A must-try here.\n\nMandazi ($1.50): a puffy and fluffy bread. Lightly sweet, so it goes well with the complimentary sweet and cinnamon-y tea (pour it yourself in the back) or with the entrees. I&#x27;d recommend ordering at least one to share, if not entirely for yourself. You might even accidentally get one when trying to order multiple Sambusos as I did.\n\nI&#x27;d definitely recommend Jubba for a great lunch or dinner for anyone who enjoys meat and starches. place itself is an extremely casual, hole-in-the-wall, mom&amp;pop kind of place, so expect a very simple decor and homey meal.  I phoned in an order for take-out and had their Kitfo \&quot;special\&quot; (with fresh jalapenos, recommended to me instead of the regular Kitfo) at medium-rare and lamb tibs at a mild spiciness.  Communication was slightly rough but eventually got through and the pickup was smooth.  The menu is relatively small, but focused on a core set of dishes.  \n\nNoteworthy is that this place has the most traditional injera I&#x27;ve found in the area so far, as their injera has considerably more teff than wheat (and a notably more sour taste and less volume to it).  I can&#x27;t tell you if it&#x27;s 100% teff, but it has that distinctive sourness and coloration to say that it&#x27;s high.  It&#x27;s expensive to import teff flour so most spots will charge a premium for it if it&#x27;s even offered at all, let alone serve it by default (absolute pro for this place in my mind, but folks may prefer the more common wheat injera).\n\nThe fact they offer variable spicy level is a departure from most Ethiopian spots I know, but the flavor for the lamb tibs came up a bit short on taste so I can&#x27;t help but feel this contributed.  I will attempt to convince my brother to brave higher heats, but keep this in mind if you modify the heat down.  The Kitfo was delicious, but notably quite spicy.  They don&#x27;t hold back when it comes to spiciness level!  Each entree had a good portion size and got a good amount of injera to boot.  \n\nOverall, I happily recommend it as a casual eatery for those looking for traditional injera in their ethiopian meals. I noticed this place was on the way and open late, so I stopped off to try it out.\n\nWhen I first arrived, the owner greeted me with a smile and a handshake. I called in my order in advance, so nearly as soon as I sat down his wife brought me my food - also with a friendly smile on her face.\n\nThis was my first experience with Ethiopian food so the presentation alone was somewhat of a spectacle. There was a big round dish (somewhat like a pizza pan) covered with Ethiopian flat bread, called Injera. Injera is made of the highly nutritious and gluten-free tef grain, which is unique to Ethiopia. On the side of the circular plate of Injera was what I would describe as a creamy Ethiopian curry - mine was vegetarian - made of puréed chickpeas, an assortment of veggies, and some delicious spices. To eat, you scoop the curry onto the flatbread and then eat it. \n\nOverall an absolutely delicious experience! The friendly, welcoming owners made my My guess is it has to do a lot with what people&#x27;s expectations of a restaurant are. \n\nThis is a mom and pop restaurant. There is no money put into presentation and service is low key. I happen to really like the low key, simpleness of it. Food is great. But note, if you are looking for an upscale, full service place, this isn&#x27;t for you.\n\nThe atmosphere here can appear intimidating. It feels like a deserted sports bar. Red walls. Pale blue ceiling. TV with sports on. 85% of the light bulbs are out. \n\nThe service is as I said, mellow. One person there to take orders and cooked. He took our order, made our food and then went back to watching the basketball game on tv. He didn&#x27;t really ask if we needed anything or check in at all, but he was present and we could get his attention if we needed to. I actually like not having a server hover of me. Nice change. \n\nWe got a veggie combo and a order of shuro for 2 people. Plenty of food. The combo would have been plenty, but just in case we got two. I wish I had taken a picture of the menu because I&#x27;m not sure exactly we ended up getting. I think we ended up with Atakilt, Gomen and Misir. I think.. =D\n\nInjera - nice texture. sourdough texture to is was spot on. Good elastic pull to it. Nice taste. \n\nAtakilt was good. Light sauce. Peppers in it packed a punch. Carrots, potato and onion were great. \n\nGomen - good texture and flavor to collard greens.\n\nShuro was interesting. I think its an acquired taste because the texture is sort of grainy and there is a lot of garlic and dried onion in it.  \n\nMisir - I think this is what we got.. I&#x27;m honestly not sure. Cons: they&#x27;re out of everything after 9pm. No kitfo. No veggie combo. No foul (pronounced \&quot;fool\&quot;). Customer service needs work. The waitress tried to talk us out of ordering gored gored saying \&quot;it&#x27;s too much spice\&quot; for us, just because we are Asian and white (one each, not both at the same time). Kept trying to sell us tibs instead. The gentleman watching this from the bar over his smartphone and beer (one of the owners?) intervened and told her it was okay. We ended up getting gored gored (raw) and shiro.\n\nAfter all that, the gored gored was not even all that spicy! It had a kick, to be sure, but it was far from the spiciest I&#x27;ve had this. It doesn&#x27;t even come close to the heat of the gored gored at Palm Grove (our favorite Ethiopian restaurant in LA), where sometimes I do have trouble having more than a few pieces. Also, we asked for this raw but it was more like medium or medium well. Not even medium rare. The flavor was delicious but we were both super disappointed that the meat wasn&#x27;t raw; that&#x27;s the whole point of Ethiopian food for us (kitfo and gored gored are traditionally served warmed but still raw).\n\nThe shiro was delicious, some of the best shiro I&#x27;ve had in recent memory. Creamy, with a great tomato-y flavor. And it arrived piping hot. Loved. It.\n\nThe injera was really great here, too. Very sour, just the way I like it. Also, it did not taste very wheat flour-y, so between the taste and the dark grey color, I would guess that they put a good amount of teff flour in their dough. (Teff is a gluten-free grain used traditionally in Ethiopia; it&#x27;s very expensive and hard to get in the US so most places here cut it with a lot of wheat flour. Some places have or can make 100% teff injera, which you can order if you&#x27;re celiac, though you usually have to pay extra for it and in some places it has to be ordered ahead of time.) As an American I admit to liking it a little more wheat-y personally, but I was impressed they did not skimp on this costly and authentic ingredient. (It definitely did not taste as teff-y as the 100% teff injera I&#x27;ve had, though, in case you&#x27;re a purist or a severe celiac allergist.)\n\nI&#x27;m very sad that we were unable to get most of the items we usually get. I didn&#x27;t feel like we fully got our Ethiopian on. I especially missed having gomen (collards) and atakilt wot (cabbage, carrots, potatoes, and chili peppers), the latter which isn&#x27;t even on their menu at all. We normally over-order and have days of leftovers; this time all that was left was a couple bits of injera (which we took home to tear up and put into a simple lettuce and tomato salad with chili peppers and non-creamy Italian dressing -- yum).\n\nParking was easy at 9pm on a Sunday night, but who knows how it is during normal business hours. Also they&#x27;re apparently not always open for the entire duration of their supposed hours (opening after 10am and closing before 2am), which is a disappointment as the fact that they say they&#x27;re open until 2am was one of our deciding factors in trying this place, wanting to scope out a potential haunt for late-night eats.\n\n3.5 for food (5 for the shiro, 4.5 for the injera, 2.5 for the gored gored not being raw -- otherwise the gored gored would have been a 4 or 4.5), 2 for service (though the gentleman at the bar&#x27;s help saved it), 5 for being open late, 2 for availability of items. I&#x27;m between a 3 and a 4 for this place, and I will bump them to a 4 due to their late hours, but I&#x27;m not sure how useful it is to be open late if they&#x27;re out of nearly everything by then.\n\nI would maybe come back but earlier in the day when hopefully they&#x27;re not out of everything. Though earlier in the day there are a lot more choices and I might just go to Walia or Zeni.\n\nYet another place with cold injera, though, so to that person who says she&#x27;s used to getting warm injera most places in the Bay area, where are you going to get all that warm injera?!?&quot;,&quot;__typename&quot;:&quot;ReviewText&quot;},&quot;$ROOT_QUERY.business({\&quot;encid\&quot;:\&quot;Hcpr8r_cbTXrqIYvdybW9Q\&quot;}).reviews({\&quot;first\&quot;:20}).edges.16&quot;:{&quot;node&quot;:{&quot;type&quot;:&quot;id&quot;,&quot;generated&quot;:true,&quot;id&quot;:&quot;$ROOT_QUERY.business({\&quot;encid\&quot;:\&quot;Hcpr8r_cbTXrqIYvdybW9Q\&quot;}).reviews({\&quot;first\&quot;:20}).edges.16.node&quot;,&quot;typename&quot;:&quot;Review&quot;},&quot;__typename&quot;:&quot;ReviewEdge&quot;},&quot;$ROOT_QUERY.business({\&quot;encid\&quot;:\&quot;Hcpr8r_cbTXrqIYvdybW9Q\&quot;}).reviews({\&quot;first\&quot;:20}).edges.17.node.author&quot;:{&quot;displayName&quot;:&quot;Jeffrey place itself is an extremely casual, hole-in-the-wall, mom&amp;pop kind of place, so expect a very simple decor and homey meal.  I phoned in an order for take-out and had their Kitfo \&quot;special\&quot; (with fresh jalapenos, recommended to me instead of the regular Kitfo) at medium-rare and lamb tibs at a mild spiciness.  Communication was slightly rough but eventually got through and the pickup was smooth.  The menu is relatively small, but focused on a core set of dishes.  \n\nNoteworthy is that this place has the most traditional injera I&#x27;ve found in the area so far, as their injera has considerably more teff than wheat (and a notably more sour taste and less volume to it).  I can&#x27;t tell you if it&#x27;s 100% teff, but it has that distinctive sourness and coloration to say that it&#x27;s high.  It&#x27;s expensive to import teff flour so most spots will charge a premium for it if it&#x27;s even offered at all, let alone serve it by default (absolute pro for this place in my mind, but folks may prefer the more common wheat injera).\n\nThe fact they offer variable spicy level is a departure from most Ethiopian spots I know, but the flavor for the lamb tibs came up a bit short on taste so I can&#x27;t help but feel this contributed.  I will attempt to convince my brother to brave higher heats, but keep this in mind if you modify the heat down.  The Kitfo was delicious, but notably quite spicy.  They don&#x27;t hold back when it comes to spiciness level!  Each entree had a good portion size and got a good amount of injera to boot.  \n\nOverall, I happily recommend it as a casual eatery for those looking for traditional injera in their ethiopian meals. I noticed this place was on the way and open late, so I stopped off to try it out.\n\nWhen I first arrived, the owner greeted me with a smile and a handshake. I called in my order in advance, so nearly as soon as I sat down his wife brought me my food - also with a friendly smile on her face.\n\nThis was my first experience with Ethiopian food so the presentation alone was somewhat of a spectacle. There was a big round dish (somewhat like a pizza pan) covered with Ethiopian flat bread, called Injera. Injera is made of the highly nutritious and gluten-free tef grain, which is unique to Ethiopia. On the side of the circular plate of Injera was what I would describe as a creamy Ethiopian curry - mine was vegetarian - made of puréed chickpeas, an assortment of veggies, and some delicious spices. To eat, you scoop the curry onto the flatbread and then eat it. \n\nOverall an absolutely delicious experience! The friendly, welcoming owners made my Cons: they&#x27;re out of everything after 9pm. No kitfo. No veggie combo. No foul (pronounced \&quot;fool\&quot;). Customer service needs work. The waitress tried to talk us out of ordering gored gored saying \&quot;it&#x27;s too much spice\&quot; for us, just because we are Asian and white (one each, not both at the same time). Kept trying to sell us tibs instead. The gentleman watching this from the bar over his smartphone and beer (one of the owners?) intervened and told her it was okay. We ended up getting gored gored (raw) and shiro.\n\nAfter all that, the gored gored was not even all that spicy! It had a kick, to be sure, but it was far from the spiciest I&#x27;ve had this. It doesn&#x27;t even come close to the heat of the gored gored at Palm Grove (our favorite Ethiopian restaurant in LA), where sometimes I do have trouble having more than a few pieces. Also, we asked for this raw but it was more like medium or medium well. Not even medium rare. The flavor was delicious but we were both super disappointed that the meat wasn&#x27;t raw; that&#x27;s the whole point of Ethiopian food for us (kitfo and gored gored are traditionally served warmed but still raw).\n\nThe shiro was delicious, some of the best shiro I&#x27;ve had in recent memory. Creamy, with a great tomato-y flavor. And it arrived piping hot. Loved. It.\n\nThe injera was really great here, too. Very sour, just the way I like it. Also, it did not taste very wheat flour-y, so between the taste and the dark grey color, I would guess that they put a good amount of teff flour in their dough. (Teff is a gluten-free grain used traditionally in Ethiopia; it&#x27;s very expensive and hard to get in the US so most places here cut it with a lot of wheat flour. Some places have or can make 100% teff injera, which you can order if you&#x27;re celiac, though you usually have to pay extra for it and in some places it has to be ordered ahead of time.) As an American I admit to liking it a little more wheat-y personally, but I was impressed they did not skimp on this costly and authentic ingredient. (It definitely did not taste as teff-y as the 100% teff injera I&#x27;ve had, though, in case you&#x27;re a purist or a severe celiac allergist.)\n\nI&#x27;m very sad that we were unable to get most of the items we usually get. I didn&#x27;t feel like we fully got our Ethiopian on. I especially missed having gomen (collards) and atakilt wot (cabbage, carrots, potatoes, and chili peppers), the latter which isn&#x27;t even on their menu at all. We normally over-order and have days of leftovers; this time all that was left was a couple bits of injera (which we took home to tear up and put into a simple lettuce and tomato salad with chili peppers and non-creamy Italian dressing -- yum).\n\nParking was easy at 9pm on a Sunday night, but who knows how it is during normal business hours. Also they&#x27;re apparently not always open for the entire duration of their supposed hours (opening after 10am and closing before 2am), which is a disappointment as the fact that they say they&#x27;re open until 2am was one of our deciding factors in trying this place, wanting to scope out a potential haunt for late-night eats.\n\n3.5 for food (5 for the shiro, 4.5 for the injera, 2.5 for the gored gored not being raw -- otherwise the gored gored would have been a 4 or 4.5), 2 for service (though the gentleman at the bar&#x27;s help saved it), 5 for being open late, 2 for availability of items. I&#x27;m between a 3 and a 4 for this place, and I will bump them to a 4 due to their late hours, but I&#x27;m not sure how useful it is to be open late if they&#x27;re out of nearly everything by then.\n\nI would maybe come back but earlier in the day when hopefully they&#x27;re not out of everything. Though earlier in the day there are a lot more choices and I might just go to Walia or Zeni.\n\nYet another place with cold injera, though, so to that person who says she&#x27;s used to getting warm injera most places in the Bay area, where are you going to get all that warm solid Ethiopian restaurant with more of a casual sports bar vibe&#x2F;setup with portions and pricing in line with other similar restaurants in the area.  Notably they have teff injera on their menu as an add-on option (\&quot;gluten free injera\&quot;), but they do charge for extra regular injera.  The place was quite spacious and service was good, though it was not terribly crowded for a Sunday night (only 1 waitress).\n\nParking situation is mostly street parking in the front or an unmarked lot in the back of the restaurant (it&#x27;s not clearly labeled so disclaimer: I&#x27;m not certain whose lot that is but a Mudai food truck was parked there).\n\nThe menu had a variety of dishes I haven&#x27;t seen too often, like shrimp tibs, mushroom tibs&#x2F;dulet, kitfo and tibs sandwiches.  Being the boring lot, my brother and I opted to get their vegetarian combo and meat combo (but hey wide variety of sampling!).  These came with respectively: a spread of red lentils (miser kik), chickpeas (ater kik), collard greens (gomen), and cabbage&#x2F;potato&#x2F;carrot (atkilt); and chicken (doro wot), kitfo, and two lamb dishes (lamb wot and lamb alicha wot).  Combos came with a house salad and two injera each.\n\nGenerally I&#x27;d say I was satisfied with most of the dishes, but their vegetable game is pretty good (generally punchier with the flavors, especially the collard greens).  The lamb wot and doro wot were very well spiced and flavor was on point.  However, the lamb alicha wot came off remarkably weak relative to the other meats and felt like the weak link there.  Kitfo and the cheese was good, though didn&#x27;t feel as strongly spiced nor as tender as I usually prefer.  The atkilt could afford to be a bit more thoroughly stewed though, as the potatoes were still quite firm, but flavor wise it was also on point.\n\nThe injera was noticeably different from most of the other places I&#x27;ve been to.  I&#x27;m no expert, but my gut tells me it&#x27;s more of a hybrid injera, with a bit of teff flour and wheat, since it was slightly more sour than typical of wheat injera (but not approaching teff injera levels of sour either).&quot;,&quot;__typename&quot;:&quot;ReviewText&quot;},&quot;$ROOT_QUERY.business({\&quot;encid\&quot;:\&quot;UI2u8LLnmAkc8MRuq9UGCQ\&quot;}).reviews({\&quot;first\&quot;:20}).edges.0&quot;:{&quot;node&quot;:{&quot;type&quot;:&quot;id&quot;,&quot;generated&quot;:true,&quot;id&quot;:&quot;$ROOT_QUERY.business({\&quot;encid\&quot;:\&quot;UI2u8LLnmAkc8MRuq9UGCQ\&quot;}).reviews({\&quot;first\&quot;:20}).edges.0.node&quot;,&quot;typename&quot;:&quot;Review&quot;},&quot;__typename&quot;:&quot;ReviewEdge&quot;},&quot;$ROOT_QUERY.business({\&quot;encid\&quot;:\&quot;UI2u8LLnmAkc8MRuq9UGCQ\&quot;}).reviews({\&quot;first\&quot;:20}).edges.1.node.author&quot;:{&quot;displayName&quot;:&quot;Gina B.&quot;,&quot;__typename&quot;:&quot;User&quot;},&quot;$ROOT_QUERY.business({\&quot;encid\&quot;:\&quot;UI2u8LLnmAkc8MRuq9UGCQ\&quot;}).reviews({\&quot;first\&quot;:20}).edges.1.node&quot;:{&quot;author&quot;:{&quot;type&quot;:&quot;id&quot;,&quot;generated&quot;:true,&quot;id&quot;:&quot;$ROOT_QUERY.business({\&quot;encid\&quot;:\&quot;UI2u8LLnmAkc8MRuq9UGCQ\&quot;}).reviews({\&quot;first\&quot;:20}).edges.1.node.author&quot;,&quot;typename&quot;:&quot;User&quot;},&quot;timeCreatedTimestamp&quot;:1647208850,&quot;rating&quot;:5,&quot;text&quot;:{&quot;type&quot;:&quot;id&quot;,&quot;generated&quot;:true,&quot;id&quot;:&quot;$ROOT_QUERY.business({\&quot;encid\&quot;:\&quot;UI2u8LLnmAkc8MRuq9UGCQ\&quot;}).reviews({\&quot;first\&quot;:20}).edges.1.node.text&quot;,&quot;typename&quot;:&quot;ReviewText&quot;},&quot;__typename&quot;:&quot;Review&quot;},&quot;$ROOT_QUERY.business({\&quot;encid\&quot;:\&quot;UI2u8LLnmAkc8MRuq9UGCQ\&quot;}).reviews({\&quot;first\&quot;:20}).edges.1.node.text&quot;:{&quot;full&quot;:&quot;I love this place. solid Ethiopian restaurant with more of a casual sports bar vibe&#x2F;setup with portions and pricing in line with other similar restaurants in the area.  Notably they have teff injera on their menu as an add-on option (\&quot;gluten free injera\&quot;), but they do charge for extra regular injera.  The place was quite spacious and service was good, though it was not terribly crowded for a Sunday night (only 1 waitress).\n\nParking situation is mostly street parking in the front or an unmarked lot in the back of the restaurant (it&#x27;s not clearly labeled so disclaimer: I&#x27;m not certain whose lot that is but a Mudai food truck was parked there).\n\nThe menu had a variety of dishes I haven&#x27;t seen too often, like shrimp tibs, mushroom tibs&#x2F;dulet, kitfo and tibs sandwiches.  Being the boring lot, my brother and I opted to get their vegetarian combo and meat combo (but hey wide variety of sampling!).  These came with respectively: a spread of red lentils (miser kik), chickpeas (ater kik), collard greens (gomen), and cabbage&#x2F;potato&#x2F;carrot (atkilt); and chicken (doro wot), kitfo, and two lamb dishes (lamb wot and lamb alicha wot).  Combos came with a house salad and two injera each.\n\nGenerally I&#x27;d say I was satisfied with most of the dishes, but their vegetable game is pretty good (generally punchier with the flavors, especially the collard greens).  The lamb wot and doro wot were very well spiced and flavor was on point.  However, the lamb alicha wot came off remarkably weak relative to the other meats and felt like the weak link there.  Kitfo and the cheese was good, though didn&#x27;t feel as strongly spiced nor as tender as I usually prefer.  The atkilt could afford to be a bit more thoroughly stewed though, as the potatoes were still quite firm, but flavor wise it was also on point.\n\nThe injera was noticeably different from most of the other places I&#x27;ve been to.  I&#x27;m no expert, but my gut tells me it&#x27;s more of a hybrid injera, with a bit of teff flour and wheat, since it was slightly more sour than typical of wheat injera (but not approaching teff injera levels of sour either).&quot;,&quot;__typename&quot;:&quot;ReviewText&quot;},&quot;$ROOT_QUERY.business({\&quot;encid\&quot;:\&quot;UI2u8LLnmAkc8MRuq9UGCQ\&quot;}).reviews({\&quot;first\&quot;:20}).edges.0&quot;:{&quot;node&quot;:{&quot;type&quot;:&quot;id&quot;,&quot;generated&quot;:true,&quot;id&quot;:&quot;$ROOT_QUERY.business({\&quot;encid\&quot;:\&quot;UI2u8LLnmAkc8MRuq9UGCQ\&quot;}).reviews({\&quot;first\&quot;:20}).edges.0.node&quot;,&quot;typename&quot;:&quot;Review&quot;},&quot;__typename&quot;:&quot;ReviewEdge&quot;},&quot;$ROOT_QUERY.business({\&quot;encid\&quot;:\&quot;UI2u8LLnmAkc8MRuq9UGCQ\&quot;}).reviews({\&quot;first\&quot;:20}).edges.1.node.author&quot;:{&quot;displayName&quot;:&quot;Gina B.&quot;,&quot;__typename&quot;:&quot;User&quot;},&quot;$ROOT_QUERY.business({\&quot;encid\&quot;:\&quot;UI2u8LLnmAkc8MRuq9UGCQ\&quot;}).reviews({\&quot;first\&quot;:20}).edges.1.node&quot;:{&quot;author&quot;:{&quot;type&quot;:&quot;id&quot;,&quot;generated&quot;:true,&quot;id&quot;:&quot;$ROOT_QUERY.business({\&quot;encid\&quot;:\&quot;UI2u8LLnmAkc8MRuq9UGCQ\&quot;}).reviews({\&quot;first\&quot;:20}).edges.1.node.author&quot;,&quot;typename&quot;:&quot;User&quot;},&quot;timeCreatedTimestamp&quot;:1647208850,&quot;rating&quot;:5,&quot;text&quot;:{&quot;type&quot;:&quot;id&quot;,&quot;generated&quot;:true,&quot;id&quot;:&quot;$ROOT_QUERY.business({\&quot;encid\&quot;:\&quot;UI2u8LLnmAkc8MRuq9UGCQ\&quot;}).reviews({\&quot;first\&quot;:20}).edges.1.node.text&quot;,&quot;typename&quot;:&quot;ReviewText&quot;},&quot;__typename&quot;:&quot;Review&quot;},&quot;$ROOT_QUERY.business({\&quot;encid\&quot;:\&quot;UI2u8LLnmAkc8MRuq9UGCQ\&quot;}).reviews({\&quot;first\&quot;:20}).edges.1.node.text&quot;:{&quot;full&quot;:&quot;I love this place. pretty much down to try anything...within reason (no furries).\n\nBut, damn...\n\nI was not prepared for Dulet.\n\nIt was first time seeing Dulet on the menu and as an offal lover, I wanted to try it.\n\nIt&#x27;s beef tripe, liver, and ground beef...\n\nBut, I didn&#x27;t know it was served entirely raw.\n\nFirst thought, \&quot;Ohhh sh*eeeet\&quot;.\n\nI legit thought my (     l     ) cheeks would be hugging the porcelain throne for the rest of the weekend.\n\nI was fine but yea be forewarned, maybe request it cooked a teeny bit if you&#x27;re scurred. I was.\n\nMaking my rounds through the various Ethiopian restaurants in the South Bay and next up, Selam!\n\nThey&#x27;ve been open for over 15 years but pretty under the radar compared to their competitors with less than 100 reviews. We were the only non-Ethiopian customers so it seemed promising. \n\nThey&#x27;re open for takeout, delivery, indoor dining (handful of tables), and outdoor dining (7-8 tables).\n\nStaff wears masks. \n\nM E N U\nBreakfast and all-day Ethiopian menu. You can mix &#x27;n match items and combos are available (best value!).\n\nRegular and gluten-free injera available. Beer and honey wine available.\n\nWith rising food costs and inflation, Selam is HELLA cheap. Literally, ordered enough for 5 people and it was only $51 pre-tip.\n\nF O O D\n***Food spread: https:&#x2F;&#x2F;bit.ly&#x2F;3vb2EHW\n\n* Doro Wot: Spicy chicken stew w&#x2F; bone-in drumstick, hardboiled egg ($15.99)\n***Available on Saturdays only.\n***Add extra hardboiled egg (+$1).\n\nDoro wot is my fav Ethiopian dish and this one was decent. Other Ethiopian restaurants usually only give you one drumstick but Selam gives you two. The chicken was tender and easily pulled off the bone with a piece of injera in hand. This is just a preference, I prefer a more saucy doro wot (this more like chicken with stewed onions). Also, it was not as richly spiced and spicy with berbere spices as I expected it to be.\n\n* 1&#x2F;2 and 1&#x2F;2 Meat Lover ($13.99)\n--Kitfo, raw: Ethiopian beef tartare w&#x2F; aiyb\nProper soft texture with a buttery mouthfeel but light in spices (no side of mitmita). The aiyb (Ethiopian cottage cheese) was mild and not overly salty which I appreciate.\n\n--Dulet, raw: Beef tripe, liver, and lean ground beef\n***Menu states lamb tripe but it&#x27;s beef tripe.\nI love tripe and liver but this was not my jam. The dulet had a gristly texture and needed more spices to mask the gamey, barnyard funk. Would be down to try it again elsewhere though.\n\n* Vegetarian &amp; Vegan Combo - Shiro: chickpea stew, misir wot: split red lentils, kik wot: yellow split peas, gomen: collard greens, and atakilt wat: cabbage, potatoes, and carrots ($13.99)\nUsually, I find that the veggie&#x2F;vegan dishes outshine the meat dishes at Ethiopian restaurants but it seems were given the Americanized version.\n\nMy fav was the misir wot which packed the most flavor but the spices and heat were very tamed for the entire combo (the gomen and atakilt wat were bland). The textures were on-point though and the lentil dishes were deliciously creamy with a bite. \n\nA basket of injera (Ethiopian fermented flatbread) is provided with every entrée, though not enough for the leftovers. The injera was soft and spongey with a subtle tang.\n\nS E R V I C E\nAll business. Order inside, they&#x27;ll bring your food out, and go inside to pay. No check-ins.\n\nArrived around 11 am and food took over 40 minutes (one of three tables). Def more of a place for a leisurely meal.\n\nA M B I A N C E\nHole-in-the wall in a dated plaza next door to Grocery Outlet.\n\nP A R K I N G\nPlenty of easy free parking in the plaza.\n\nOverall, Selam serves great value Ethiopian fare with huge portions. The spices&#x2F;flavors were too toned down for me though but you can&#x27;t beat the prices. \n\nMaybe you have to specify, \&quot;I want it LIT on both ends, It&#x27;s fantastic. Plenty of vegan options. The vegetarian combo is $14 and it comes with six different dishes (mesir wot, kik alicha, green lentils, atakilt wot, gomen, shuro) plus a salad in the middle. Mushroom tibs and timatim fitfit each cost $13.\n\nThe food is savory, flavorful, comforting, and leaves your hands smelling like delicious spices for hours. All the warm stews are melt-in-your-mouth soft and each has a distinct flavor profile. You can get a variety of root vegetables, greens, and hearty lentils, juxtaposed by the refreshing accompanying salad and crunchy jalapeños garnishing everything.\n\nThe portion size is quite generous - each dish comes on top of a full-sized piece of injera on a big plate, and has a basket of injera rolls on the side. \n\nThe indoor space is a little small, so it might be difficult to dine with a big group. it.\n\nIt&#x27;s beef tripe, liver, and ground beef...\n\nBut, I didn&#x27;t know it was served entirely raw.\n\nFirst thought, \&quot;Ohhh sh*eeeet\&quot;.\n\nI legit thought my (     l     ) cheeks would be hugging the porcelain throne for the rest of the weekend.\n\nI was fine but yea be forewarned, maybe request it cooked a teeny bit if you&#x27;re scurred. I was.\n\nMaking my rounds through the various Ethiopian restaurants in the South Bay and next up, Selam!\n\nThey&#x27;ve been open for over 15 years but pretty under the radar compared to their competitors with less than 100 reviews. We were the only non-Ethiopian customers so it seemed promising. \n\nThey&#x27;re open for takeout, delivery, indoor dining (handful of tables), and outdoor dining (7-8 tables).\n\nStaff wears masks. \n\nM E N U\nBreakfast and all-day Ethiopian menu. You can mix &#x27;n match items and combos are available (best value!).\n\nRegular and gluten-free injera available. Beer and honey wine available.\n\nWith rising food costs and inflation, Selam is HELLA cheap. Literally, ordered enough for 5 people and it was only $51 pre-tip.\n\nF O O D\n***Food spread: https:&#x2F;&#x2F;bit.ly&#x2F;3vb2EHW\n\n* Doro Wot: Spicy chicken stew w&#x2F; bone-in drumstick, hardboiled egg ($15.99)\n***Available on Saturdays only.\n***Add extra hardboiled egg (+$1).\n\nDoro wot is my fav Ethiopian dish and this one was decent. Other Ethiopian restaurants usually only give you one drumstick but Selam gives you two. The chicken was tender and easily pulled off the bone with a piece of injera in hand. This is just a preference, I prefer a more saucy doro wot (this more like chicken with stewed onions). Also, it was not as richly spiced and spicy with berbere spices as I expected it to be.\n\n* 1&#x2F;2 and 1&#x2F;2 Meat Lover ($13.99)\n--Kitfo, raw: Ethiopian beef tartare w&#x2F; aiyb\nProper soft texture with a buttery mouthfeel but light in spices (no side of mitmita). The aiyb (Ethiopian cottage cheese) was mild and not overly salty which I appreciate.\n\n--Dulet, raw: Beef tripe, liver, and lean ground beef\n***Menu states lamb tripe but it&#x27;s beef tripe.\nI love tripe and liver but this was not my jam. The dulet had a gristly texture and needed more spices to mask the gamey, barnyard funk. Would be down to try it again elsewhere though.\n\n* Vegetarian &amp; Vegan Combo - Shiro: chickpea stew, misir wot: split red lentils, kik wot: yellow split peas, gomen: collard greens, and atakilt wat: cabbage, potatoes, and carrots ($13.99)\nUsually, I find that the veggie&#x2F;vegan dishes outshine the meat dishes at Ethiopian restaurants but it seems were given the Americanized version.\n\nMy fav was the misir wot which packed the most flavor but the spices and heat were very tamed for the entire combo (the gomen and atakilt wat were bland). The textures were on-point though and the lentil dishes were deliciously creamy with a bite. \n\nA basket of injera (Ethiopian fermented flatbread) is provided with every entrée, though not enough for the leftovers. The injera was soft and spongey with a subtle tang.\n\nS E R V I C E\nAll business. Order inside, they&#x27;ll bring your food out, and go inside to pay. No check-ins.\n\nArrived around 11 am and food took over 40 minutes (one of three tables). Def more of a place for a leisurely meal.\n\nA M B I A N C E\nHole-in-the wall in a dated plaza next door to Grocery Outlet.\n\nP A R K I N G\nPlenty of easy free parking in the plaza.\n\nOverall, Selam serves great value Ethiopian fare with huge portions. The spices&#x2F;flavors were too toned down for me though but you can&#x27;t beat the prices. \n\nMaybe you have to specify, \&quot;I want it LIT on both ends, Mushroom tibs and timatim fitfit each cost $13.\n\nThe food is savory, flavorful, comforting, and leaves your hands smelling like delicious spices for hours.
